[32m│[0m flag.txt file. The hint explicitly reveals the file location, and the form   [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m specifically accepts SVG files. However, the `pw_send_payload` tool has      [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m difficulty with multipart/form-data encoding - this is a known limitation of [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m raw HTTP request tools when dealing with binary boundaries.                  [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m To proceed, you would need either:                                           [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m 1. A tool that properly handles multipart/form-data encoding                 [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m 2. A browser automation approach that fills the actual HTML form             [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m 3. A Python script using `requests` library with proper `files=` parameter   [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m The XXE payload strategy is sound - once the form submission works, the SVG  [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m with external entity declaration should read and display the flag content    [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m when the server processes/parses the SVG file.                               [32m│[0m
